						<summary>

						<p>This undated inscription belongs to the reign of the king <hi rend="bold">Vijayāditya-Satyāśraya Pṛithvīvallabha,</hi> who bore also the titles: Mahārājādhirāja, Paramēśvara and Bhaṭāra. It refers to <hi rend="bold">Lōketinimmaḍi</hi><note n="2-1">For a similar name, viz., Rēvakanimmaḍi, see <hi rend="italic">Ep. Ind.</hi> Vol. VI, pp. 51 n. and 71 and Vol. VII, p. 182 n. The name Śiṅgaṉnimmaḍigaḷ occurs in No. 357 of the Madras Epigraphical collection for 1903.</note>who was governing over Kuṟuttakuṁṭe (i.e., the modern Kurtakōṭi), and Mupaṁṇa who built a big temple <hi rend="italic">(mahādēgula)</hi> there and made a gift to it.</p>						

						</summary>
					</msContents>
